66</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Hues&amp;rft.au=John+Chamberlain&amp;rft.au=Norman+Egbert+McClure%2C+ed.&amp;rft.btitle=The+Letters+%5BMemoirs+of+the+American+Philosophical+Society%2C+vol.+12%2C+pts.+1%E2%80%932%5D&amp;rft.date=1939&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.pages=566&amp;rft.place=Philadelphia%2C+Penn.&amp;rft.pub=American+Philosophical+Society&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F221477966&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span><span class="citation-comment" style="display:none; color:#33aa33; margin-left:0.3em">CS1 maint: Extra text: authors list (<a href="/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Extra_text:_authors_list" title="Category:CS1 maint: Extra text: authors list">link</a>)</span>: see Kargon, "The Wizard Earl and the New Science" in <i>Atomism in England</i>, pp. 5\xe2\x80\x9317 at 16.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-34"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFJohn_AubreyOliver_Lawson_Dick.2C_ed.1975" class="citation"><a href="/wiki/John_Aubrey" title="John Aubrey">John Aubrey</a>; Oliver Lawson Dick, ed. (1975), <i><a href="/wiki/Brief_Lives" title="Brief Lives">Aubrey\'s Brief Lives</a></i>, London: <a href="/wiki/Secker_and_Warburg" class="mw-redirect" title="Secker and Warburg">Secker and Warburg</a>, p.&#160;123, <a href="/wiki/OCLC" title="OCLC">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.worldcat.org/oclc/1981442">1981442</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Hues&amp;rft.au=John+Aubrey&amp;rft.au=Oliver+Lawson+Dick%2C+ed.&amp;rft.btitle=Aubrey%27s+Brief+Lives&amp;rft.date=1975&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.pages=123&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=Secker+and+Warburg&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F1981442&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span><span class="citation-comment" style="display:none; color:#33aa33; margin-left:0.3em">CS1 maint: Extra text: authors list (<a href="/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Extra_text:_authors_list" title="Category:CS1 maint: Extra text: authors list">link</a>)</span>, critiqued by Shirley, <i>Thomas Harriot</i>, pp. 364\xe2\x80\x93365. See <cite id="CITEREFAllan_Chapman1995" class="citation"><a href="/wiki/Allan_Chapman_(historian)" title="Allan Chapman (historian)">Allan Chapman</a> (1995), "The Astronomical Work of Thomas Harriot (1560\xe2\x80\x931621)", <i>Quarterly Journal of the Royal Astronomical Society</i>, <b>36</b>: 97\xe2\x80\x93107 at 99, <a href="/wiki/Bibcode" title="Bibcode">Bibcode</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1995QJRAS..36...97C">1995QJRAS..36...97C</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Hues&amp;rft.atitle=The+Astronomical+Work+of+Thomas+Harriot+%281560%E2%80%931621%29&amp;rft.au=Allan+Chapman&amp;rft.date=1995&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Quarterly+Journal+of+the+Royal+Astronomical+Society&amp;rft.pages=97-107+at+99&amp;rft.volume=36&amp;rft_id=info%3Abibcode%2F1995QJRAS..36...97C&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-35"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-35">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Feingold says that Hues became "a type of private tutor to Oxford men": <cite id="CITEREFMordechai_Feingold1984" class="citation">Mordechai Feingold (1984), <i>The Mathematicians\' Apprenticeship: Science, Universities and Society in England, 1560\xe2\x80\x931640</i>, Cambridge: <a href="/wiki/Cambridge_University_Press" title="Cambridge University Press">Cambridge University Press</a>, p.&#160;84, <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-521-25133-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-521-25133-4">978-0-521-25133-4</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Hues&amp;rft.au=Mordechai+Feingold&amp;rft.btitle=The+Mathematicians%27+Apprenticeship%3A+Science%2C+Universities+and+Society+in+England%2C+1560%E2%80%931640&amp;rft.date=1984&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-521-25133-4&amp;rft.pages=84&amp;rft.place=Cambridge&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-36"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-36">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">In <i>Historia et antiquitates universitatis Oxoniensis</i> (<i>History and Antiquities of the University of Oxford</i>, 1674), vol. 2, p. 361, notice of Hues\' death was given under St. Mary Hall as follows: "Oxonii in parochi\xc3\xa2 Sancti Aldati, inque Domicilio speciatim lapides [<i>sic</i>: lapideo?], e regione insignis Afri [<i>sic</i>: Apri?] c\xc3\xa6rulei, fatis concessit, et in ecclesi\xc3\xa2 \xc3\x86dis Christi Cathedrali humatus fuit an: dom: CI\xc6\x86DXXXII [<i>sic</i>: CI\xc6\x86DCXXXII]" (He yielded to the <a href="/wiki/Parcae" title="Parcae">Fates</a> at Oxford, in the <a href="/wiki/St_Aldate%27s,_Oxford" title="St Aldate\'s, Oxford">parish of St. Aldate</a>, specifically in the Stone House, in the neighbourhood of the Blue Boar sign, and was buried in the church of Christ Church Cathedral in the year of our Lord 1532 [<i>sic</i>: 1632]). <cite class="citation"><i>Historia et antiquitates universitatis Oxoniensis duobus voluminibus comprehens\xc3\xa6 [History and Antiquities of the University of Oxford Taken together in Two Volumes]</i>, Oxford: E Theatro Sheldoniano [<a href="/wiki/Sheldonian_Theatre" title="Sheldonian Theatre">Sheldonian Theatre</a>, <a href="/wiki/University_of_Oxford" title="University of Oxford">University of Oxford</a>], 1674, <a href="/wiki/OCLC" title="OCLC">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.worldcat.org/oclc/13439733">13439733</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Hues&amp;rft.btitle=Historia+et+antiquitates+universitatis+Oxoniensis+duobus+voluminibus+comprehens%C3%A6+%5BHistory+and+Antiquities+of+the+University+of+Oxford+Taken+together+in+Two+Volumes%5D&amp;rft.date=1674&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.place=Oxford&amp;rft.pub=E+Theatro+Sheldoniano+%26%2391%3BSheldonian+Theatre%2C+University+of+Oxford%26%2393%3B&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F13439733&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>, was a Latin translation by Richard Peers and Richard Reeve under the direction of Dr. <a href="/wiki/John_Fell_(clergyman)" class="mw-redirect" title="John Fell (clergyman)">John Fell</a> of an English manuscript by Anthony \xc3\xa0 Wood which the University purchased in 1670. The manuscript itself was later published as <cite id="CITEREFAnthony_.C3.A0_WoodJohn_Gutch1786.E2.80.931790" class="citation"><a href="/wiki/Anthony_Wood" title="Anthony Wood">Anthony \xc3\xa0 Wood</a>; <a href="/wiki/John_Gutch" title="John Gutch">John Gutch</a> (1786\xe2\x80\x931790), <i>The History &amp; Antiquities of the Colleges and Halls in the University of Oxford&#160;... Now First Published in English, from the Original Manuscript in the Bodleian Library&#160;... with a Continuation to the Present Time, by the Editor, John Gutch. (Appendix to the History and Antiquities of the Colleges and Halls in the University of Oxford&#160;... containing Fasti Oxonienses, or a Commentary on the Supreme Magistrates of the University: by Anthony \xc3\xa0 Wood, M.A. Now First Published in English&#160;... with a Continuation to the Present Time, also Additions and Corrections&#160;... and Indexes to the Whole, by the Editor, John Gutch.)</i>, Oxford: <a href="/wiki/Oxford_University_Press" title="Oxford University Press">Clarendon Press</a>, <a href="/wiki/OCLC" title="OCLC">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.worldcat.org/oclc/84810015">84810015</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Hues&amp;rft.au=Anthony+%C3%A0+Wood&amp;rft.au=John+Gutch&amp;rft.btitle=The+History+%26+Antiquities+of+the+Colleges+and+Halls+in+the+University+of+Oxford+...+Now+First+Published+in+English%2C+from+the+Original+Manuscript+in+the+Bodleian+Library+...+with+a+Continuation+to+the+Present+Time%2C+by+the+Editor%2C+John+Gutch.+%28Appendix+to+the+History+and+Antiquities+of+the+Colleges+and+Halls+in+the+University+of+Oxford+...+containing+Fasti+Oxonienses%2C+or+a+Commentary+on+the+Supreme+Magistrates+of+the+University%3A+by+Anthony+%C3%A0+Wood%2C+M.A.+Now+First+Published+in+English+...+with+a+Continuation+to+the+Present+Time%2C+also+Additions+and+Corrections+...+and+Indexes+to+the+Whole%2C+by+the+Editor%2C+John+Gutch.%29&amp;rft.date=1786%2F1790&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.place=Oxford&amp;rft.pub=Clarendon+Press&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F84810015&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>. See Markham, "Introduction", <i>Tractatus de globis</i>, p. xxxvii, n. 1.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-37"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-37">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>Historia et antiquitates universitatis Oxoniensis</i>, vol. 2, p. 534. The brass is also referred to at p. 288: "In lamin\xc3\xa2 \xc5\x93ne\xc3\xa2, eidem pariati [<i>sic</i>: parieti?] impact\xc3\xa2 talem cernis inscriptionem" (On the copper plate, driven to the same wall, one sees such an inscription). See Markham, "Introduction", <i>Tractatus de globis</i>, p. xxxvii, n. 1.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-38"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-38">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The title is from <cite id="CITEREFHelen_M._Wallis1955" class="citation"><a href="/wiki/Helen_Wallis" title="Helen Wallis">Helen M. Wallis</a> (1955), "Further light on the Molyneux globes", <i><a href="/wiki/The_Geographical_Journal" title="The Geographical Journal">The Geographical Journal</a></i>, Blackwell Publishing, <b>121</b> (3): 304, <a href="/wiki/JSTOR" title="JSTOR">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.jstor.org/stable/1790894">1790894</a>, <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.2307%2F1790894">10.2307/1790894</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Hues&amp;rft.atitle=Further+light+on+the+Molyneux+globes&amp;rft.au=Helen+M.+Wallis&amp;rft.date=1955&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Geographical+Journal&amp;rft.pages=304&amp;rft.volume=121&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F1790894&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.2307%2F1790894&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>, and the <a href="/wiki/Imprint_(bibliography)" class="mw-redirect" title="Imprint (bibliography)">imprint</a> information from <a href="/wiki/WorldCat" title="WorldCat">WorldCat</a> (<a href="/wiki/OCLC" title="OCLC">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.worldcat.org/oclc/42811612">42811612</a>). According to Markham, "Introduction", <i>Tractatus de globis</i>, pp. xxxvii\xe2\x80\x93xxxviii, the title of this version is <i>Tractaut of te handebingen van het gebruych der hemel siker ende aertscher globe</i>, and it was printed in Antwerp.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-39"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-39">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFJ.J._O.27ConnorE.F._Robertson2006" class="citation">J.J. O\'Connor; E.F. Robertson (August 2006), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.webcitation.org/5h1wyOlQX?url=http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Biographies/Herigone.html"><i>Pierre H\xc3\xa9rigone</i></a>, The MacTutor History of Mathematics archive, School of Mathematics and Statistics, <a href="/wiki/University_of_St_Andrews" title="University of St Andrews">University of St Andrews</a>, archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Biographies/Herigone.html">the original</a> on 25 May 2009<span class="reference-accessdate">, retrieved <span class="nowrap">7 November</span> 2008</span></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Hues&amp;rft.au=E.F.+Robertson&amp;rft.au=J.J.+O%27Connor&amp;rft.btitle=Pierre+H%C3%A9rigone&amp;rft.date=2006-08&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.pub=The+MacTutor+History+of+Mathematics+archive%2C+School+of+Mathematics+and+Statistics%2C+University+of+St+Andrews&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk%2F~history%2FBiographies%2FHerigone.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-40"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-40">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">According to Markham, "Introduction", <i>Tractatus de globis</i>, at p. xxxviii, this version was published by Jodocus Hondius in 1624. However, WorldCat (<a href="/wiki/OCLC" title="OCLC">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.worldcat.org/oclc/8909075">8909075</a>) suggests that the 1624 version was in Latin, not Dutch.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-41"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-41">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">WorldCat (<a href="/wiki/OCLC" title="OCLC">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.worldcat.org/oclc/61335670">61335670</a>) suggests that printings of this work were also made in 1639; see also <cite class="citation"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://openlibrary.org/b/OL7015375M"><i>A learned treatise of globes both coelestiall and terrestriall, with their severall uses, by Robert Hues</i></a>, Open Library, <a href="/wiki/Internet_Archive" title="Internet Archive">Internet Archive</a><span class="reference-accessdate">, retrieved <span class="nowrap">10 November</span> 2008</span></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Hues&amp;rft.btitle=A+learned+treatise+of+globes+both+coelestiall+and+terrestriall%2C+with+their+severall+uses%2C+by+Robert+Hues&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.pub=Open+Library%2C+Internet+Archive&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fopenlibrary.org%2Fb%2FOL7015375M&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>. According to Markham, "Introduction", <i>Tractatus de globis</i>, p. xxxix, although the title page of the work states that the translator was "John Chilmead", this is generally believed to be an error as no such person was known to have lived at the time. Instead, the translator is believed to be <a href="/wiki/Edmund_Chilmead" title="Edmund Chilmead">Edmund Chilmead</a> (1610\xe2\x80\x931653), a translator, man of letters and music teacher who graduated in 1628 and was a chaplain of <a href="/wiki/Christ_Church,_Oxford" title="Christ Church, Oxford">Christ Church, Oxford</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-42"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-42">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Markham, "Introduction", <i>Tractatus de globis</i>, pp. xxxix\xe2\x80\x93xl.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-43"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-43">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">See <cite class="citation"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.webcitation.org/5h1x5roKC?url=http://www.mhs.ox.ac.uk/measurer/text/fig22.htm"><i>Figure 22: Title-page of the Dutch edition of Hues\'s account of the globes, illustrating a celestial globe by Hondius</i></a>, The Measurers: A Flemish Image of Mathematics in the Sixteenth Century, <a href="/wiki/Museum_of_the_History_of_Science,_Oxford" title="Museum of the History of Science, Oxford">Museum of the History of Science, Oxford</a>, 7 August 1995, archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.mhs.ox.ac.uk/measurer/text/fig22.htm#figure22">the original</a> on 25 May 2009<span class="reference-accessdate">, retrieved <span class="nowrap">11 November</span> 2008</span></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Hues&amp;rft.btitle=Figure+22%3A+Title-page+of+the+Dutch+edition+of+Hues%27s+account+of+the+globes%2C+illustrating+a+celestial+globe+by+Hondius&amp;rft.date=1995-08-07&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.pub=The+Measurers%3A+A+Flemish+Image+of+Mathematics+in+the+Sixteenth+Century%2C+Museum+of+the+History+of+Science%2C+Oxford&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.mhs.ox.ac.uk%2Fmeasurer%2Ftext%2Ffig22.htm%23figure22&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-44"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-44">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.webcitation.org/5g0IYEOFc?url=http://purl.pt/40/1/obras/p-nunes-na-europa/pn_conhecimento_manuscritos_80.html"><i>HUES, Robert, 1553\xe2\x80\x931632. Tractatvs de globis coelesti et terrestri eorvmqve vsv</i></a>, <a href="/wiki/Biblioteca_Nacional_de_Portugal" title="Biblioteca Nacional de Portugal">Biblioteca Nacional de Portugal</a>, 2002, archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://purl.pt/40/1/obras/p-nunes-na-eur